               <head>Jurisprudence and correspondence, 2 items (a-b)</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Miscellaneous collection of works on jurisprudence and official correspondence by <persName key="person_f7377" role="aut">Muḥammad Karīm Allāh</persName>. 
Not dated. 
Partially foliated. 
Paper dust wrapper (BEIC legal publication on legislation for 1852); watermarked (lion rampant guardant holding sceptre in crowned oval frame; not dated); label, creased and stained. 
Folios detached; large wormholes. 
                  </summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic </textLang>
                  <msItem class="https://lccn.loc.gov/sh85068454" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_85x-item1">
                     <locus from="1r" to="10r">ff. 1r-10r </locus>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic </textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 85* a. 
</p>
                        <p>Rough draft of an original but apparently untitled treatise on jurisprudence by an unnamed author. </p>
                        <p>Defective at beginning. 
</p>
                        <p>Not dated at end. Datable to the early nineteenth century. 
</p>
                        <p>Rough nastaʿlīq, mostly without diacritics. 
</p>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100074" n="2" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_85x-item2">
                     <locus from="12r" to="23r ">ff. 12r-23r </locus>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f7377">Muḥammad Karīm Allāh</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" key="person_f7377">محمّد كريم الله</persName>
                     </author>
                     <note>
                        <p>Delhi Persian 85* b. 
</p>
                        <p>Untitled treatise comprised of petitions and official correspondence addressed to kings and lords (salāṭīn va khavānīn), compiled by <persName key="person_f7377" role="aut">Muḥammad Karīm Allāh</persName>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>The author wrote the work for his students and especially for his middling son, <persName key="person_f8261" role="oth">Muḥammad Yaḥyá</persName>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated at end. Datable to the early nineteenth century. 
</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic </textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
